\subsection{Single-Column Model Verification and Observation Comparison}
\label{subsec:numerical_verification}

We verify the prognostic 4D GSPT SBL formulation by comparing SCM (Single-Column Model) simulations against observational data from two highly contrasting field campaigns: the Cooperative Atmosphere-Surface Exchange Study 1999 (\textbf{CASES99}) and the Fluxes Over Snow Surfaces (\textbf{FLOSS}) experiment.

\paragraph{Physical Setup and Surface Drag Forcing.}
The primary physical difference between these environments lies in their surface boundary properties. Our numerical simulations initialize both setups under clear nocturnal radiative cooling conditions, but vary the local aerodynamic roughness length $z_{0m}$ and thermal capacity $C_s$:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{CASES99 (Grassland Plains):} With a moderate roughness length ($z_{0m} \approx 0.02\,\mathrm{m}$), the ground exerts a strong frictional torque on the surface wind field. This high-drag regime acts as a continuous source of mechanical shear, which physically expands the active critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$ and anchors the boundary layer in a weakly turbulent, coupled state under low geostrophic wind speeds.
    \item \textbf{FLOSS (Fluxes Over Snow Surfaces):} Smooth snow cover features an exceptionally low roughness length ($z_{0m} \approx 10^{-4}\,\mathrm{m}$), which suppresses mechanical shear production. Furthermore, the high thermal insulation of the snowpack isolates the skin layer from geothermal soil heat flux, accelerating radiative cooling. This rapid cooling shifts the paraboloid critical manifold downward along the TKE axis. Consequently, the FLOSS regime requires much higher geostrophic winds ($U_g > 8\,\mathrm{m\,s}^{-1}$) to sustain active turbulence; under weaker forcing, the system undergoes a rapid, complete turbulent collapse.
\end{itemize}

