\paragraph{Manifold Approximation Analysis.}
As shown in Table~\ref{tab:site_comparison_metrics}, the FLOSS simulations yield a significantly lower manifold fit RMSE for both TKE and velocity. Because the aerodynamic smoothness of the snowpack dampens mechanical shear, the fast TKE coordinate is constrained tightly to the stable, non-turbulent residual sheet $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{lam}}$ for the majority of the night.

In contrast, the larger roughness length of CASES99 drives continuous, intermittent turbulence. The state-space trajectories of CASES99 undergo broader excursions around the nonlinear, curved knees of the active critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$, which naturally increases the geometric projection error (higher RMSE) while maintaining a higher overall trajectory capture rate within the active turbulent envelope.